# Cloudflare Pages routing. Real static assets (index.html, sandbox.html,
# privacy.html, /assets/*, …) are served before the 200 rewrite below applies.
#
# NOTE: do NOT add a top-level /404.html file. Cloudflare Pages only runs its
# SPA fallback (the `/* /index.html 200` rule below) when there is NO top-level
# 404.html — when one exists, Pages serves it for every not-found path and the
# rewrite never fires, 404'ing all deep links (/create, /play) on refresh.
# Unknown routes are handled in-app by react-router's catch-all instead.
# Also: 404 is not a valid _redirects status (only 200 / 301-308); never use it.
#
# Known trade-off: a MISSING /assets/* hashed chunk resolves to index.html as
# 200 text/html (failing the browser's module import), not a 404 — _redirects
# cannot return 404, so there is no way to guard against it here. Low risk:
# deploys are atomic and index.html is must-revalidate, so a poisoned URL is
# always a stale hash no current client requests; self-healing on reload. Real
# 404s for missing assets would require a Pages Function or nested 404.html.
#
# SPA fallback for the client-side router (react-router). Routes like /play and
# /create have no backing file, so direct loads / refreshes resolve to index.html
# and the router takes over.
/* /index.html 200
